english:
  title: 'A Ritual Offering at the Stele: For the Master on His Memorial Day'
  author: Seok Cheon-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I reflect that the Great Teaching shines in solitary splendor,
    Its lineage commanded by Nagarjuna of old.
    Nine generations have spread its fragrance far,
    And the echoes reached the lands across the eastern sea.

    But when the Five Dynasties fell into decline,
    The center grew turbid while the borderlands stayed clear.
    The dharma flowed through the six mountains in mighty streams,
    And thus our way came to flourish greatly.

    Why did fortune suddenly turn its face?
    The thread of transmission grew thin as gossamer.
    The ancient buddhas and patriarchs have long since passed—
    Who will labor to restore what has weakened?

    Our Master possessed a beauty beyond measure,
    Born of celestial essence, standing tall and resolute.
    In a world of confusion, few could recognize his worth;
    I grieve, standing alone, lonely and forsaken.

    Yet guarding his faith with steadfast devotion,
    He remained unmoved by the doubts of multitudes.
    When karmic conditions ripened and transformation unfolded,
    All the world suddenly turned and followed his way.

    I, obtuse and lacking in quickness of mind,
    Was blessed to receive his teachings in his presence.
    The burden is heavy, the path stretches long—
    I wandered midway, confused and uncertain.

    Though I wished to shoulder the great work, my strength fell short;
    I could only draw water and gather firewood in service.
    How could I have known my wishes would not be fulfilled,
    That suddenly he would return to the source?

    Time passes swiftly, relentless as flowing water—
    Four years have already slipped away.
    The temple halls lie desolate and empty,
    And the monastery's affairs decline day by day.

    Not long ago I oversaw the builders' labor;
    They came and told me the great stone was finished.
    We raised this monument to honor his memory,
    That its brilliance might shine through endless ages.

    But illness seized me and lingered long,
    So I could not perform the rites as intended.
    Alas, misfortune has accumulated upon me,
    And medicine brings no relief.

    Should I not seek the physician or the shaman's aid?
    Yet I fear their confused and contradictory counsel.
    The frost and snow descend in abundance;
    The mushrooms and cassia wither before their time.

    I lie still in silence and darkness—
    This is fate; what more can be said?

    It is finished. If my Master will not grant me his compassion,
    Where shall I turn for aid unseen?

    Now his memorial day arrives in perfect time,
    And his voice and form seem present still.
    I offer fragrant orchids gathered in clusters,
    And burn the sweet herbs and aromatics.

    May my sincere devotion reach the heavens—
    O Spirit, descend and witness; do not turn away in darkness.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Nagarjuna (Dragon Tree): The legendary Indian Buddhist philosopher credited with establishing the Madhyamaka school, here representing the transmission of Buddhist teaching.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The five dynasties and ten kingdoms period: A reference to the chaotic political period in East Asian history when Buddhism''s institutional strength waned in the center but persisted in peripheral regions.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Great Teaching: Buddhism, treated here as a sacred transmission with an unbroken lineage.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Memorial day ritual: A traditional East Asian Buddhist practice of honoring a deceased teacher on the anniversary of his passing.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The imagery of drawing water and gathering firewood: Common Buddhist metaphors for humble spiritual service.'
